","1295–Female":"1295–Deceased","1362":"1362","1295":"1295","1382":"1382","1290":"1290","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","about 1318":"about 1318","1346":"1346","1344":"1344","1453":"1453","1342":"1342","about 1341":"about 1341","about 1342":"about 1342","1417":"1417","1318":"1318","1328":"1328","England":"England","London, England":"London, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705192,"age":10,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705193,"age":19,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705195,"age":64,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Margaret Dolsely was born about 1318, in London, England, her father, Simon Dolsely, was 30 and her mother, Mrs Simon Dolsley, was 25. She married John Gisors about 1341, in London, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 2 daughters."},"et":{"about 1318–":"umbes 1318–Surnud","1318–Female":"1318–Surnud","1315–Male":"1315–Surnud","1342–1417":"1342–1417","1344–Female":"1344–Surnud","1346–Male":"1346–Surnud","1290–1362":"1290–1362","1295–Female":"1295–Surnud","1362":"1362","1295":"1295","1382":"1382","1290":"1290","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","about 1318":"umbes 1318","1346":"1346","1344":"1344","1453":"1453","1342":"1342","about 1341":"umbes 1341","about 1342":"umbes 1342","1417":"1417","1318":"1318","1328":"1328","England":"England","London, England":"London, England"},"fi":{"about 1318–":"noin 1318–Kuollut","1318–Female":"1318–Kuollut","1315–Male":"1315–Kuollut","1342–1417":"1342–1417","1344–Female":"1344–Kuollut","1346–Male":"1346–Kuollut","1290–1362":"1290–1362","1295–Female":"1295–Kuollut","1362":"1362","1295":"1295","1382":"1382","1290":"1290","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","about 1318":"noin 1318","1346":"1346","1344":"1344","1453":"1453","1342":"1342","about 1341":"noin 1341","about 1342":"noin 1342","1417":"1417","1318":"1318","1328":"1328","England":"England","London, England":"London, England"},"fr":{"about 1318–":"environ 1318–Décédée","1318–Female":"1318–Décédée","1315–Male":"1315–Décédé","1342–1417":"1342–1417","1344–Female":"1344–Décédée","1346–Male":"1346–Décédé","1290–1362":"1290–1362","1295–Female":"1295–Décédée","1362":"1362","1295":"1295","1382":"1382","1290":"1290","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","about 1318":"environ 1318","1346":"1346","1344":"1344","1453":"1453","1342":"1342","about 1341":"environ 1341","about 1342":"environ 1342","1417":"1417","1318":"1318","1328":"1328","England":"Angleterre","London, England":"Londres, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Lorsque Margaret Dolsely est née environ 1318, à Londres, Angleterre, son père, Simon Dolsely, avait 30 ans et sa mère, Mrs Simon Dolsley, avait 25 ans. Elle a épousé John Gisors environ 1341, à Londres, Angleterre. Ils ont eu au moins 1 fils et 2 filles."},"de":{"about 1318–":"um 1318–Verstorbe